subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Female
(male unknown): flagellum uniformly brown on dorsal side, paler ventrally (
Figs 93, 95
); legs uniformly pale (
Fig. 91
); fore wing hyaline (
Fig. 99
); body setation short (longest genal setae about 1/5 length of tegula) and whitish (
Figs 93, 95, 96, 99
); head in profile with face only slightly convex at toruli level (
Fig. 95
); eye height 1.55–1.80× length of malar space; eye in lateral view not distinctly inclined relative to vertical axis of head (
Fig. 95
); lower margin of toruli slightly above or level with lower margin of eyes (
Fig. 93
); antenna (
Figs 93, 95
) with scape barely reaching median ocellus; clava width 1.1–1.5× width of F1; proximal funicular segments quadrate to slightly transverse, distal funicular segments slightly to moderately transverse (F5 width 1.1–1.5× length); mesosoma length about equal to width; MV length 2.0–2.5× width; fore wing speculum present, although small (
Fig. 99
).

Colour.
Head and mesosoma mostly black, with weak, mainly blue-green reflections (
Figs 93–96
); pronotum, mesopleuron and propodeum from yellowish-brown to dark brown (
Figs 97, 98
); membranous area between pronotum and fore coxa whitish (
Fig. 97
). Gaster dorsally light brown to dark brown, lighter ventrally, from whitish to light brown (
Fig. 91
). Eyes from pale reddish-grey to dark red; ocelli whitish (
Figs 93, 94
). Antenna (
Figs 93, 95
) with scape and pedicel yellowish-brown; flagellum uniformly brown. Mandibles yellowish-brown, teeth reddish-brown. Legs (
Fig. 91
) entirely pale yellow to yellowish-brown except for darker pretarsi. Wings hyaline, tegula and venation yellowish-brown, venation paler ventrally (
Fig. 99
). Body setation whitish, wing setation brownish (
Figs 93, 96, 99
).

Structure.
Head. Longest genal setae about 1/5 length of tegula. Head in profile with face slightly convex at toruli level (
Fig. 95
). Lower margin of toruli from about level with to slightly above lower eye margins (
Fig. 93
). Scape not or barely reaching median ocellus. Antenna only slightly clavate, clava 1.1–1.5× as wide as F1 (6.5:4.5) (
Figs 93, 95
). Eyes oval, inner margins slightly diverging ventrally (
Fig. 93
); eye in lateral view not distinctly inclined relative to vertical axis of head (
Fig. 95
). Head width 2.1–2.4× length in dorsal view (47:22) and 1.2–1.3× height in frontal view (47:40). POL 1.4–1.6× as long as OOL (12:8). Eye height 1.20–1.25× length (22:18) and 1.55–1.80× malar space (22:12). Scape length from slightly shorter (usually) to virtually equal to eye height (20:22). Head width about 1.2× length of pedicel plus flagellum (47:40). F1 width 1.0–1.2× length (4.5:4.0); F5 width 1.1–1.5× length (6:5); clava length 1.8–2.1× width (12.0:6.5).

Mesosoma. Scutellar spine small, hardly visible among dense setae (
Fig. 96
). Propodeum smooth, median carina thin (
Fig. 98
). Fore wing (
Fig. 99
) with small speculum; parastigma with hyaline break. Mesosoma length 1.0–1.1× width (41:41), width 1.3–1.5× height (41:32). Mesoscutum width 2.3–2.8× length (41:16). Mesoscutellum length about equal to width (20:20). Propodeum length about 0.3× mesoscutellum length (6:20). Fore wing length 1.85–2.10× width (87:47). MV length 2.0–2.5× width (8.5:4.0); SV 1.6–2.6× MV (17.0:8.5); PV 2.5–3.8× MV (20.0:8.5).

Gaster. Short ovate, from slightly longer to distinctly shorter than head plus mesosoma (
Figs 91, 92
); length 1.3–2.1× width (43:33).
